The paper discusses user studies and user preferences in interacting with dialogue systems, which falls under the category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The paper also discusses natural language processing and feature gaps in dialogue systems, which are relevant to computational linguistics (cs.CL). The study focuses on older adults, which could fall under the category of cyberpsychology (cs.CY) or social and information networks (cs.SI) as it relates to understanding user behavior and preferences. Finally, the paper proposes a new user modeling framework, which could fall under the category of computer vision and pattern recognition (cs.CC) as it involves developing a model to understand user behavior.
